1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,160
 So up to now, we've done all the easy stuff.

2
00:00:03,160 --> 00:00:07,960
 So it's time to do the linked TreeMaP.

3
00:00:07,960 --> 00:00:12,200
 Which really is kind of a modern, flexible key value store.

4
00:00:12,200 --> 00:00:14,400
 This is a nice key value store that you

5
00:00:14,400 --> 00:00:18,400
 would want to use if you were a software developer.

6
00:00:18,400 --> 00:00:24,880
 Our linked TreeMaP is ordered, like Python order dictionaries.

7
00:00:24,880 --> 00:00:29,680
 It stays sorted, meaning that not only does it stay in order,

8
00:00:29,680 --> 00:00:31,320
 it stays in sorted order.

9
00:00:31,320 --> 00:00:34,920
 We insert things, and they go in an order, like a Java TreeMaP.

10
00:00:34,920 --> 00:00:40,400
 You can be iterated, like a C++ map or an ordered dictionary,

11
00:00:40,400 --> 00:00:42,040
 but not a Java TreeMaP.

12
00:00:42,040 --> 00:00:45,120
 This just boggles my mind why you can't--

13
00:00:45,120 --> 00:00:47,560
 well, we'll talk about actually why they didn't do it.

14
00:00:47,560 --> 00:00:51,600
 But it's not that hard.

15
00:00:51,600 --> 00:00:53,480
 And we're going to have fast lookups.

16
00:00:53,480 --> 00:00:56,720
 So the problem with a list map is it's

17
00:00:56,720 --> 00:00:58,120
 got a lot of nice features.

18
00:00:58,120 --> 00:00:59,760
 And we can make a sorted list map,

19
00:00:59,760 --> 00:01:03,440
 and we're going to in this section.

20
00:01:03,440 --> 00:01:05,800
 But the problem with a list map is lookup is slow.

21
00:01:05,800 --> 00:01:09,160
 And so we're going to actually pretty much use the tree part

22
00:01:09,160 --> 00:01:10,400
 to do fast lookup.

23
00:01:10,400 --> 00:01:13,760
 And you can see this in 6.5.2 of the textbook.

24
00:01:13,760 --> 00:01:16,200
 So we are going to do something that's

25
00:01:16,200 --> 00:01:17,560
 pretty common in data structures.

26
00:01:17,560 --> 00:01:19,880
 And that is we're going to maintain two--

27
00:01:19,880 --> 00:01:21,240
 whatever the entries, and they're

28
00:01:21,240 --> 00:01:24,160
 going to maintain simultaneously a sorted linked

29
00:01:24,160 --> 00:01:27,620
 list through the entries and a binary tree.

30
00:01:27,620 --> 00:01:29,480
 And so we're going to look at them separately,

31
00:01:29,480 --> 00:01:32,800
 and then we're ultimately going to find them together.

32
00:01:32,800 --> 00:01:34,960
 We're going to put them together.

33
00:01:34,960 --> 00:01:39,200
 So let's talk about what a tree is.

34
00:01:39,200 --> 00:01:45,400
 A tree is a structure that the TreeMaP entry you see

35
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:47,120
 has a left and a right.

36
00:01:47,120 --> 00:01:49,520
 So the things to the left are things

37
00:01:49,520 --> 00:01:52,320
 where the key is lower than the current, right?

38
00:01:52,320 --> 00:01:54,360
 So H equals 42.

39
00:01:54,360 --> 00:01:57,680
 The question is, where would A go?

40
00:01:57,680 --> 00:01:59,480
 Well, A goes to the left.

41
00:01:59,480 --> 00:02:00,960
 Where would T go?

42
00:02:00,960 --> 00:02:02,680
 Well, T goes to the right.

43
00:02:02,680 --> 00:02:07,680
 So the idea of the tree is that whatever entry you're in,

44
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:09,640
 there's a key in the entry.

45
00:02:09,640 --> 00:02:11,600
 And then you can either go left or right

46
00:02:11,600 --> 00:02:14,920
 based on the comparison of the key.

47
00:02:14,920 --> 00:02:18,480
 And instead of having a head and a tail, there is just a root.

48
00:02:18,480 --> 00:02:22,200
 So the root is the top entry of this tree.

49
00:02:22,200 --> 00:02:24,440
 And then there's a series of left and right choices

50
00:02:24,440 --> 00:02:25,600
 that you make.

51
00:02:25,600 --> 00:02:28,560
 And each entry has a left and a right.

52
00:02:28,560 --> 00:02:32,720
 And the TreeMaP entry has a key value pair.

53
00:02:32,720 --> 00:02:36,400
 And we're going to keep key and value as public,

54
00:02:36,400 --> 00:02:38,120
 because it's just an entry.

55
00:02:38,120 --> 00:02:40,560
 But now there is no next, right?

56
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:43,080
 This is why we are using abstraction,

57
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:46,240
 because we're not even going to give them a next.

58
00:02:46,240 --> 00:02:49,120
 We're going to have a left and a right, OK?

59
00:02:49,120 --> 00:02:50,760
 And we're not going to show that.

60
00:02:50,760 --> 00:02:52,720
 We're not going to let people see that.

61
00:02:52,720 --> 00:02:55,160
 We're just going to give them a set of methods

62
00:02:55,160 --> 00:02:56,560
 to mess with our TreeMaP.

63
00:02:56,560 --> 00:02:58,400
 And we're going to deal with all this stuff.

64
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:00,640
 And we need a left and a right to do it.

65
00:03:00,640 --> 00:03:03,360
 So just taking a look at how it works

66
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:05,040
 is let's just say we're going to--

67
00:03:05,040 --> 00:03:07,360
 in this current tree that I've sort of built,

68
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:08,560
 they're not always balanced.

69
00:03:08,560 --> 00:03:10,600
 I happen to balance it just because it looks better

70
00:03:10,600 --> 00:03:12,480
 on PowerPoint slides.

71
00:03:12,480 --> 00:03:17,080
 But let's just say we're going to insert in this tree

72
00:03:17,080 --> 00:03:22,920
 g equals 25, so it's got a key of g and a value of 25.

73
00:03:22,920 --> 00:03:26,280
 So what you do is you start at the root, and you compare it.

74
00:03:26,280 --> 00:03:29,720
 And you say, oh, g is less than h.

75
00:03:29,720 --> 00:03:32,200
 So we're going to go down the left-hand side.

76
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:34,600
 So you can think of it as you're walking down

77
00:03:34,600 --> 00:03:36,040
 the left-hand side.

78
00:03:36,040 --> 00:03:39,680
 Then you are encountering d equals 8.

79
00:03:39,680 --> 00:03:43,240
 And then you're like, OK, g is greater than d.

80
00:03:43,240 --> 00:03:47,280
 So we've got to take the-- it's like driving a car.

81
00:03:47,280 --> 00:03:52,480
 Turn right at intersection d.

82
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:53,520
 And so we do.

83
00:03:53,520 --> 00:03:55,120
 And we're working our way down.

84
00:03:55,120 --> 00:03:58,160
 And now we have-- we're looking at intersection f.

85
00:03:58,160 --> 00:04:00,400
 And we've really got to go left or right.

86
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:03,240
 And so f, g.

87
00:04:03,240 --> 00:04:04,600
 g is greater than f.

88
00:04:04,600 --> 00:04:08,000
 And so we're going to go to the right, not the left.

89
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:09,240
 So we do.

90
00:04:09,240 --> 00:04:13,640
 And so that basically is the path that we took.

91
00:04:13,640 --> 00:04:17,160
 And so to insert g into the tree,

92
00:04:17,160 --> 00:04:23,680
 we find the greatest value less than, which is f.

93
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:25,960
 And you're kind of inserting it, if you think about it,

94
00:04:25,960 --> 00:04:28,280
 between f and h.

95
00:04:28,280 --> 00:04:32,160
 So the next higher one in the tree is h.

96
00:04:32,160 --> 00:04:34,760
 And the next lower one in the tree is f.

97
00:04:34,760 --> 00:04:37,500
 And that was the trip we did.

98
00:04:37,500 --> 00:04:41,120
 I like to think of this sort of trickling down the tree

99
00:04:41,120 --> 00:04:46,280
 and making these decisions as almost like a pachinko machine,

100
00:04:46,280 --> 00:04:47,840
 where you hit the balls.

101
00:04:47,840 --> 00:04:49,500
 They go ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding.

102
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:51,040
 It's not random, of course.

103
00:04:51,040 --> 00:04:52,440
 It's very precise.

104
00:04:52,440 --> 00:04:54,920
 But it is kind of like you stop at the top

105
00:04:54,920 --> 00:04:58,680
 and you make a bunch of binary left, right decisions.

106
00:04:58,680 --> 00:05:03,800
 And eventually you find yourself somewhere at the bottom.

107
00:05:03,800 --> 00:05:08,160
 And so if we kind of look at the tree map put,

108
00:05:08,160 --> 00:05:11,760
 and we are going to start at the root,

109
00:05:11,760 --> 00:05:16,120
 and then we're going to do a comparison,

110
00:05:16,120 --> 00:05:19,760
 and if we find it, the comparison is going to be 0.

111
00:05:19,760 --> 00:05:21,920
 We update the value.

112
00:05:21,920 --> 00:05:26,600
 And if we don't find it and it's less than, we're going to go left.

113
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:28,920
 And if it's greater than, we're going to go right.

114
00:05:28,920 --> 00:05:31,840
 And so this is basically the idea.

115
00:05:31,840 --> 00:05:35,120
 This while loop will trickle down the tree going left

116
00:05:35,120 --> 00:05:36,120
 and going right.

117
00:05:36,120 --> 00:05:40,840
 And it will either find the value if there's a match.

118
00:05:40,840 --> 00:05:43,120
 Like if we're looking for f, we'd have found it,

119
00:05:43,120 --> 00:05:45,440
 and we'd have stopped, and we would have returned.

120
00:05:45,440 --> 00:05:48,280
 If we're looking for g, we won't find it,

121
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:52,680
 but we will find where we're supposed to insert it.

122
00:05:52,680 --> 00:05:54,400
 So the last thing that we talk to,

123
00:05:54,400 --> 00:05:58,560
 which g will find its way down to the right of f,

124
00:05:58,560 --> 00:06:01,080
 we will find where to put it.

125
00:06:01,080 --> 00:06:03,080
 So as long as the tree is correctly maintained,

126
00:06:03,080 --> 00:06:06,720
 you will either find a match or you will find the right place

127
00:06:06,720 --> 00:06:07,640
 to insert it.

128
00:06:07,640 --> 00:06:12,400
 And the tree will-- it's not guaranteed to be balanced.

129
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:15,400
 There's further algorithms that can make the tree balanced.

130
00:06:15,400 --> 00:06:20,800
 But the key thing is that the order will be right.

131
00:06:20,800 --> 00:06:23,080
 So by inserting, following these rules,

132
00:06:23,080 --> 00:06:26,480
 following this algorithm, the order will be right,

133
00:06:26,480 --> 00:06:30,320
 and you will always find the right place to put it.

134
00:06:30,320 --> 00:06:32,920
 Or you will find a matching place.

135
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:35,280
 And think about how dictionaries work, right?

136
00:06:35,280 --> 00:06:40,280
 You say x sub hello equals something.

137
00:06:40,280 --> 00:06:43,600
 Well, there's either going to be a hello key in there or not.

138
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:45,840
 If there's not, we're going to put it in.

139
00:06:45,840 --> 00:06:47,400
 If there is, we're going to update it.

140
00:06:47,400 --> 00:06:51,840
 And that's what this code does.

141
00:06:51,840 --> 00:06:54,000
 We're going to create a new tree map.

142
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:57,160
 We're going to put h equals 22, and then we're

143
00:06:57,160 --> 00:07:00,640
 going to do h equals 42, which replaces h, right?

144
00:07:00,640 --> 00:07:02,920
 Then we're going to do d equals 8.

145
00:07:02,920 --> 00:07:05,240
 Then we do b equals 1, 2, 3.

146
00:07:05,240 --> 00:07:07,080
 And then we're going to do f equals 6.

147
00:07:07,080 --> 00:07:09,120
 And it turns out I'm kind of doing this in order

148
00:07:09,120 --> 00:07:10,840
 so it doesn't get too long on the page.

149
00:07:10,840 --> 00:07:12,240
 And then I'm going to do a dump.

150
00:07:12,240 --> 00:07:14,680
 And remember how important a debug is.

151
00:07:14,680 --> 00:07:17,080
 When I first wrote this code, you can darn well bet you

152
00:07:17,080 --> 00:07:19,280
 that I had map dump.

153
00:07:19,280 --> 00:07:21,400
 It was map put, map dump, map put, map dump,

154
00:07:21,400 --> 00:07:24,920
 map put, map dump, so I could see what it does.

155
00:07:24,920 --> 00:07:28,000
 And so the dump, if you look at the dump,

156
00:07:28,000 --> 00:07:31,720
 then we put in k and m and j, and then we dump it again.

157
00:07:31,720 --> 00:07:34,960
 And so what I've done is, if you look at the map output,

158
00:07:34,960 --> 00:07:38,160
 you see that the map output has these h equals 42.

159
00:07:38,160 --> 00:07:40,560
 And then it's kind of trying to give you

160
00:07:40,560 --> 00:07:44,240
 some sense of the tree-ness of it,

161
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:51,600
 meaning that the b equals 123, f equals 6, and d equals 8.

162
00:07:51,600 --> 00:07:53,520
 The number of vertical bars tell you

163
00:07:53,520 --> 00:07:55,240
 how deep in the tree you are.

164
00:07:55,240 --> 00:07:59,320
 And so you can see that the immediate child nodes of h

165
00:07:59,320 --> 00:08:01,760
 in the second dump are d and k.

166
00:08:01,760 --> 00:08:04,200
 And the child nodes of k are j and m.

167
00:08:04,200 --> 00:08:05,480
 So you can draw this all up.

168
00:08:05,480 --> 00:08:08,400
 And so the idea of my dump code is

169
00:08:08,400 --> 00:08:11,080
 I'm trying to sort of draw you a tree.

170
00:08:11,080 --> 00:08:12,720
 So here is the dump code.

171
00:08:12,720 --> 00:08:16,680
 Now this is very, very different.

172
00:08:16,680 --> 00:08:20,880
 And literally, this is the first time-- well,

173
00:08:20,880 --> 00:08:22,640
 I talked about recursions and functions.

174
00:08:22,640 --> 00:08:24,760
 I talked about stack frames and stuff like that.

175
00:08:24,760 --> 00:08:28,640
 But if you go all the way back to Python for everybody,

176
00:08:28,640 --> 00:08:31,480
 I delay talking about recursion until there's

177
00:08:31,480 --> 00:08:33,160
 a real value for it.

178
00:08:33,160 --> 00:08:39,160
 And it turns out, this is a beautiful use of recursion.

179
00:08:39,160 --> 00:08:41,160
 And if you didn't write this recursively,

180
00:08:41,160 --> 00:08:43,200
 you'd probably have to write your own stack.

181
00:08:43,200 --> 00:08:45,720
 And that would be like a bummer, because we're

182
00:08:45,720 --> 00:08:47,400
 going to recursively go down the tree,

183
00:08:47,400 --> 00:08:49,160
 and we're going to keep track of the depth.

184
00:08:49,160 --> 00:08:51,000
 And the idea of the depth is it tells me

185
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:52,840
 how many vertical bars to print.

186
00:08:52,840 --> 00:08:55,840
 So we come in, and we're pointed at a particular place

187
00:08:55,840 --> 00:08:58,480
 in the tree, maybe the root, maybe the top one.

188
00:08:58,480 --> 00:09:00,640
 And depth is going to be 0.

189
00:09:00,640 --> 00:09:03,680
 And so if cur is null, we're done.

190
00:09:03,680 --> 00:09:05,240
 A key thing to recursion is you've

191
00:09:05,240 --> 00:09:08,440
 got to have a way to get out.

192
00:09:08,440 --> 00:09:12,400
 So if we get to the end of some tree, subtree,

193
00:09:12,400 --> 00:09:14,360
 and we get to a null, we go left or right,

194
00:09:14,360 --> 00:09:16,320
 and that it's a null, don't print anything out.

195
00:09:16,320 --> 00:09:17,000
 Just you're done.

196
00:09:17,000 --> 00:09:21,040
 You've gone one beyond the leaf of the tree.

197
00:09:21,040 --> 00:09:23,680
 And cur is null, so just return.

198
00:09:23,680 --> 00:09:26,040
 Then what we do is we have a for loop,

199
00:09:26,040 --> 00:09:29,880
 depending on depth, that prints vertical bar space.

200
00:09:29,880 --> 00:09:32,760
 That spaces it over.

201
00:09:32,760 --> 00:09:35,920
 And we're going to go down the left tree,

202
00:09:35,920 --> 00:09:37,540
 and then we're going to come back,

203
00:09:37,540 --> 00:09:38,960
 and we're going down the right tree.

204
00:09:38,960 --> 00:09:41,120
 And this is what's called a depth-first search

205
00:09:41,120 --> 00:09:44,240
 for those computer science nerds.

206
00:09:44,240 --> 00:09:47,080
 And so we're going to go down the left.

207
00:09:47,080 --> 00:09:49,740
 And you'll notice that when we go down the left,

208
00:09:49,740 --> 00:09:52,320
 if the left is not equal to null,

209
00:09:52,320 --> 00:09:56,600
 we are going to dump the tree on the left

210
00:09:56,600 --> 00:09:58,080
 with depth equals depth plus 1.

211
00:09:58,080 --> 00:09:59,840
 And so if we start with a depth of 0,

212
00:09:59,840 --> 00:10:00,920
 that's going to become 1.

213
00:10:00,920 --> 00:10:03,160
 And then if we recursively go down further,

214
00:10:03,160 --> 00:10:05,360
 then it's going to be 2.

215
00:10:05,360 --> 00:10:12,120
 And then when that recursion comes back,

216
00:10:12,120 --> 00:10:13,640
 if cur right is not equal to null,

217
00:10:13,640 --> 00:10:15,440
 we're going to dump the tree on the right.

218
00:10:15,440 --> 00:10:18,940
 So what you see is dump the tree on the left recursively,

219
00:10:18,940 --> 00:10:20,600
 which means go all the way down the left,

220
00:10:20,600 --> 00:10:23,280
 then come back up, then dump the right node,

221
00:10:23,280 --> 00:10:26,060
 then come back up, go up again, and dump the right node.

222
00:10:26,060 --> 00:10:28,840
 And so you see this like how the order-- this

223
00:10:28,840 --> 00:10:35,760
 is a depth-first search of H. We're going down past D.

224
00:10:35,760 --> 00:10:38,960
 Then we're going even further past B.

225
00:10:38,960 --> 00:10:41,360
 And then we're coming up from B, and we're going back down

226
00:10:41,360 --> 00:10:45,640
 from D to F. We're coming up from F. Then we come up from D.

227
00:10:45,640 --> 00:10:50,000
 Then we go across H. And then we go down to K.

228
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:54,040
 Then we go to the left of K, which is J. We go back up.

229
00:10:54,040 --> 00:10:57,120
 And then we go to the right of K, which is M.

230
00:10:57,120 --> 00:11:00,200
 And then we go back up, go back up, and we're done.

231
00:11:00,200 --> 00:11:05,020
 So the calling sequence to this is tree map, dump tree,

232
00:11:05,020 --> 00:11:07,660
 self-root with a depth of 0.

233
00:11:07,660 --> 00:11:08,480
 I will say this.

234
00:11:08,480 --> 00:11:09,980
 When I wrote this code the first time,

235
00:11:09,980 --> 00:11:12,680
 I had printfs all over the place.

236
00:11:12,680 --> 00:11:16,560
 Now I pretty much know how to do a depth-first search of a tree.

237
00:11:16,560 --> 00:11:22,680
 But still, in a debugging, sometimes you

238
00:11:22,680 --> 00:11:24,080
 make your tree incorrectly.

239
00:11:24,080 --> 00:11:26,240
 And your debugging is like, huh?

240
00:11:26,240 --> 00:11:29,880
 That doesn't look like what I thought it was going to be.

241
00:11:29,880 --> 00:11:34,080
 And so don't be ashamed if you have

242
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:37,040
 to put print statements in all over the place.

243
00:11:37,040 --> 00:11:38,560
 First, get your dump working.

244
00:11:38,560 --> 00:11:40,520
 Just make sure your dump works, because then you

245
00:11:40,520 --> 00:11:43,840
 can debug everything else with the dump.

246
00:11:43,840 --> 00:11:46,400
 And the get's pretty simple.

247
00:11:46,400 --> 00:11:48,840
 And we've got the default. We've got the key.

248
00:11:48,840 --> 00:11:50,080
 And we've got the tree.

249
00:11:50,080 --> 00:11:52,440
 So we're going to start a while loop, where

250
00:11:52,440 --> 00:11:55,800
 we're going to go down left, right, left, right, left, right.

251
00:11:55,800 --> 00:11:57,760
 So we're going to start at the root.

252
00:11:57,760 --> 00:11:59,920
 We're going to compare the key to the key we're searching

253
00:11:59,920 --> 00:12:01,640
 for, the current key.

254
00:12:01,640 --> 00:12:05,320
 If they're the same, then return the value.

255
00:12:05,320 --> 00:12:07,960
 We could do this recursively, but you

256
00:12:07,960 --> 00:12:10,640
 don't do recursion if you don't need to.

257
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:15,840
 If the key we're looking for is less than the key we found,

258
00:12:15,840 --> 00:12:17,320
 we're going to go down the left.

259
00:12:17,320 --> 00:12:19,080
 And if the current key-- otherwise, we're

260
00:12:19,080 --> 00:12:20,200
 going to go down the right.

261
00:12:20,200 --> 00:12:22,820
 And so you can see this thing is just going to pachinko its way

262
00:12:22,820 --> 00:12:25,540
 down, ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, to the right spot.

263
00:12:25,540 --> 00:12:29,160
 And if it gets to null, then we return the default.

264
00:12:29,160 --> 00:12:31,160
 Remember, this is like a dictionary.

265
00:12:31,160 --> 00:12:34,640
 If the key's not there on a get, we return the default.

266
00:12:34,640 --> 00:12:44,400
 You can see why Guido van Rossum, in Christmas 1987,

267
00:12:44,400 --> 00:12:48,420
 created a function called get, which looked for a key

268
00:12:48,420 --> 00:12:51,440
 and took a default value.

269
00:12:51,440 --> 00:12:54,800
 Because this code is what you write,

270
00:12:54,800 --> 00:12:57,220
 what I'm going to return null and then I have an if statement.

271
00:12:57,220 --> 00:12:58,120
 Heck no.

272
00:12:58,120 --> 00:13:00,520
 Just pass in a default. If you get to the bottom of the tree

273
00:13:00,520 --> 00:13:02,880
 and you haven't found it, return the default.

274
00:13:02,880 --> 00:13:05,960
 If I want it to be null, I can make the default null, right?

275
00:13:05,960 --> 00:13:07,080
 Away we go.

276
00:13:07,080 --> 00:13:09,240
 So this is beautiful.

277
00:13:09,240 --> 00:13:10,840
 This is beautiful.

278
00:13:10,840 --> 00:13:20,880
 So from that beauty, both the dump are beautiful

279
00:13:20,880 --> 00:13:24,640
 and the get is beautiful.

280
00:13:24,640 --> 00:13:26,800
 Iterator is a pain.

281
00:13:26,800 --> 00:13:31,280
 You just can't easily build an iterator for a pure tree.

282
00:13:31,280 --> 00:13:34,320
 If you have nothing more than that tree.

283
00:13:34,320 --> 00:13:39,200
 So a list map can support an ordered iterator.

284
00:13:39,200 --> 00:13:44,520
 We saw before a hash map can support an unordered iterator.

285
00:13:44,520 --> 00:13:47,840
 But a tree map cannot support an iterator

286
00:13:47,840 --> 00:13:49,720
 without building some kind of a stack.

287
00:13:49,720 --> 00:13:55,680
 And the problem is that the concept of current

288
00:13:55,680 --> 00:13:57,800
 is just so complex.

289
00:13:57,800 --> 00:14:00,800
 When we're doing recursion, the concept of current

290
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:03,440
 is just so implicit.

291
00:14:03,440 --> 00:14:06,000
 It's actually in the call stack, the notion of current.

292
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:10,640
 Because there's really, when you're doing the dump,

293
00:14:10,640 --> 00:14:12,400
 you have a call stack of currents.

294
00:14:12,400 --> 00:14:14,800
 And then when you go back up the call stack,

295
00:14:14,800 --> 00:14:16,200
 you're getting a different current.

296
00:14:16,200 --> 00:14:17,240
 So you're switching back.

297
00:14:17,240 --> 00:14:20,560
 And so you either have to make your own stack of currents.

298
00:14:20,560 --> 00:14:22,840
 You could build an iterator for a tree,

299
00:14:22,840 --> 00:14:24,520
 but you have to build a stack.

300
00:14:24,520 --> 00:14:28,520
 So a lot of folks sort of don't want to do that.

301
00:14:28,520 --> 00:14:31,160
 We could build a stack, but we're not going to.

302
00:14:31,160 --> 00:14:32,920
 So what we're going to do is we're

303
00:14:32,920 --> 00:14:35,960
 going to do a technique for our iterator

304
00:14:35,960 --> 00:14:38,860
 that is a common technique.

305
00:14:38,860 --> 00:14:42,560
 When you have a data structure that almost does what you want,

306
00:14:42,560 --> 00:14:45,160
 and then you have another data structure that

307
00:14:45,160 --> 00:14:47,640
 does what you want, you combine them.

308
00:14:47,640 --> 00:14:49,320
 So if you look at this tree, there's

309
00:14:49,320 --> 00:14:53,160
 a lot of nice things for searching, for replacing,

310
00:14:53,160 --> 00:14:54,520
 for inserting.

311
00:14:54,520 --> 00:14:58,040
 And it does all that very fast, because it's actually

312
00:14:58,040 --> 00:15:00,560
 log n, because the height of the tree

313
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:02,760
 is log base 2 of the width of the tree,

314
00:15:02,760 --> 00:15:04,360
 the number of items in the tree.

315
00:15:04,360 --> 00:15:05,960
 So it's log base 2-ish.

316
00:15:05,960 --> 00:15:07,920
 So it's super fast.

317
00:15:07,920 --> 00:15:08,880
 All my trees are small.

318
00:15:08,880 --> 00:15:12,280
 But if these trees get big, they're super fast.

319
00:15:12,280 --> 00:15:14,520
 It goes down, the pachinko sits way down

320
00:15:14,520 --> 00:15:16,120
 to the bottom really fast.

321
00:15:16,120 --> 00:15:18,440
 But I can't easily build an iterator.

322
00:15:18,440 --> 00:15:20,120
 So what I'm going to do is I'm going

323
00:15:20,120 --> 00:15:23,400
 to add to this a linked list.

324
00:15:23,400 --> 00:15:27,920
 But I'm going to have the linked list simultaneously

325
00:15:27,920 --> 00:15:31,040
 working with the tree.

326
00:15:31,040 --> 00:15:33,600
 So each of these items is going to have

327
00:15:33,600 --> 00:15:36,800
 a next and a pre and a left and a right.

328
00:15:36,800 --> 00:15:41,080
 And we're going to almost write the code mentally independently

329
00:15:41,080 --> 00:15:45,040
 for the tree code and the linked list code.

330
00:15:45,040 --> 00:15:47,920
 So we're ultimately going to combine these things together.

331
00:15:47,920 --> 00:15:52,360
 There's not a separate linked list and a separate tree.

332
00:15:52,360 --> 00:15:56,120
 It looks like this in a linked tree map.

333
00:15:56,120 --> 00:15:58,680
 So think of each one of these things having a next

334
00:15:58,680 --> 00:16:01,240
 and a pre and a left and a right.

335
00:16:01,240 --> 00:16:04,920
 And we maintain them in such a way when we're doing inserts

336
00:16:04,920 --> 00:16:07,800
 that everything works perfectly.

337
00:16:07,800 --> 00:16:10,840
 So we're going to simultaneously maintain

338
00:16:10,840 --> 00:16:14,200
 with the same entries a tree and a list.

339
00:16:14,200 --> 00:16:17,760
 But we're only going to use the list to build the iterator.

340
00:16:17,760 --> 00:16:19,800
 And we're going to make this a sorted list,

341
00:16:19,800 --> 00:16:21,840
 because these things are in order.

342
00:16:21,840 --> 00:16:24,840
 The tree is helping us quickly find the place to put it.

343
00:16:24,840 --> 00:16:27,560
 But also, we're to put it in order.

344
00:16:27,560 --> 00:16:29,680
 So let's take advantage of that.

345
00:16:29,680 --> 00:16:36,160
 So this is a sorted, ordered dictionary in Python lingo.

346
00:16:36,160 --> 00:16:40,840
 So just remember that these entries, these list tree map

347
00:16:40,840 --> 00:16:46,640
 entries, are simultaneously participating in a tree

348
00:16:46,640 --> 00:16:48,720
 and at the same time in another layer,

349
00:16:48,720 --> 00:16:52,400
 as it were, participating in a linked list.

350
00:16:52,400 --> 00:16:56,240
 The tree map, which is the tree map structure,

351
00:16:56,240 --> 00:16:58,880
 has a head and a root.

352
00:16:58,880 --> 00:17:01,240
 Because at the same time, tree map

353
00:17:01,240 --> 00:17:04,720
 is both a tree and a linked list.

354
00:17:04,720 --> 00:17:09,760
 And the map entry is going to have a next and a left

355
00:17:09,760 --> 00:17:10,800
 and a right.

356
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:13,680
 And again, you just almost keep these things

357
00:17:13,680 --> 00:17:16,000
 separate in your mind.

358
00:17:16,000 --> 00:17:17,520
 When we're doing tree things, we're

359
00:17:17,520 --> 00:17:19,320
 going to use left and right and root.

360
00:17:19,320 --> 00:17:20,560
 And when we're doing list things,

361
00:17:20,560 --> 00:17:22,600
 we're going to use head and next.

362
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:24,320
 And these are things now by now that should

363
00:17:24,320 --> 00:17:27,120
 be sort of familiar to you.

364
00:17:27,120 --> 00:17:29,240
 So this is the structure that we're

365
00:17:29,240 --> 00:17:31,600
 going to build and maintain.

366
00:17:31,600 --> 00:17:36,080
 And up next, we're going to build the put code,

367
00:17:36,080 --> 00:17:39,900
 or this combined two-layer data structure that

368
00:17:39,900 --> 00:17:44,360
 has a tree and a sorted linked list all at the same time.

